   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Discussion Questions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c6494022",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Similar to what we did in Scenario 3, let's look at different quantile values to decide what proportion of jobs to assign to renewable energy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "80238dd9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Decide which jobs to assign to renewable region\n",
    "cpu_threshold = jobs_with_energy[\"cpu_cores\"].quantile(\n",
    "    # enter a choice between 0 and 1 here\n",
    "    -1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "green_jobs = jobs_with_energy[jobs_with_energy[\"cpu_cores\"] >= cpu_threshold]\n",
    "dirty_jobs = jobs_with_energy[jobs_with_energy[\"cpu_cores\"] < cpu_threshold]\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the new total emissions\n",
    "smart_emissions = compute_emissions(green_jobs, carbon_intensity[renewable_region]) + \\\n",
    "                  compute_emissions(dirty_jobs, carbon_intensity[coal_region])\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the new total runtime (with parallelization)\n",
    "smart_runtime = max(compute_total_runtime(green_jobs, max_cores_per_region[renewable_region]),\n",
    "                    compute_total_runtime(dirty_jobs, max_cores_per_region[coal_region]))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"High-CPU jobs to {renewable_region}: {smart_emissions:.4f} kg CO2, Runtime: {smart_runtime:.2f} h\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7cfe28ad",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Comment on what you believe is the most appropriate threshold given the tradeoff between emissions and runtime."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d18f3dc6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A reasonable threshold is around the 0.5 quantile (median) or slightly higher such as 0.6 to 0.7 because assigning only high CPU jobs to renewable regions reduces emissions while avoiding long runtimes caused by limited resources, creating a balanced tradeoff between efficiency and sustainability."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "969f5aa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### In this notebook, we calculate emissions and runtimes as the inputs of our cost-benefit analysis. Name and explain at least one other cost or benefit that is not considered here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "056d51e2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One important factor not considered is financial cost since electricity prices vary by region and renewable energy can sometimes be more expensive, and another factor is data transfer latency and cost because moving jobs across regions can introduce delays and additional overhead."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3a1a5dfb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### List at least two different stakeholders that would be affected by a strategic decision regarding the assignment of resources explored in this notebook. In your opinion, which stakeholder's interests are most compelling?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3edf9331",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Stakeholders include cloud providers who manage infrastructure, companies running computations who care about cost and performance, end users who rely on fast services, and society which is affected by emissions, and the most compelling stakeholder is society because environmental impacts like climate change affect everyone long term."
   ]
  }
